<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-3-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Second Order Homogeneous Linear Differential Equations</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Understand methods of solutions for second order homogeneous linear differential equations
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      We now discuss the Wronskian of solutions of second order homogeneous linear equations.
    </p>

    <p> Let <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> be solutions of the homogeneous linear differential equation <me>
      y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0,
      </me> where <m>a_1(x)</m> and <m>a_0(x)</m> are
      continuous functions on an interval <m>I.</m> The <term>
        <em>Wronskian</em>
      </term> of <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m>, denoted by <m>W(y_1, y_2)(x)</m>
      , <m>W(y_1(x), y_2(x))</m>, or simply <m>W(x)</m>, is defined as <me>
        W(x) = \begin{vmatrix} y_1(x) &amp; y_2(x) \\ y_1'(x) &amp; y_2'(x) \end{vmatrix} =
      y_1(x)y_2'(x) - y_1'(x)y_2(x).
      </me>
      Let us examine the derivative of the Wronskian <m> W(x).</m> We have <me>
        \begin{split} W'(x) &amp;= y_1(x)y_2''(x)+y'_1(x)y'_2(x) - y_1'(x)y'_2(x)- y_2(x)y''_1(x)\\
      &amp;=y_1(x)y_2''(x)-y_2(x)y''_1(x)\\ &amp;=y_1(x)\big(-a_1(x) y'_2(x)- a_0(x)y_2(x)\big)\\
      &amp;\quad -y_2(x)\big(-a_1(x) y'_1(x)- a_0(x)y_1(x)\big)\\ &amp;=- a_1(x) W(x), \end{split}
      </me>
      where we used <m>y_1''(x) = -a_1(x) y'_1(x)- a_0(x)y_1(x)</m> and <m>y_2''(x) = -a_1(x)
      y'_2(x)- a_0(x)y_2(x).</m> It then follows that <men xml:id="eq-Abel-formula">
        W(x) =W(x_0)\; e^{-\int_{x_0}^x a_1(t)\, dt},
      </men> where <m>x_0</m> is a
      fixed number in <m>I.</m> The formula <xref ref="eq-Abel-formula" /> is known as <term>Abel’s
      formula</term>. It follows from this formula that <m>W(x)</m> is a constant when <m>a_1(x) =0</m>
      on <m>I.</m> Also, if <m>W(x_0)= 0</m>, then <m>W(x) = 0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I.</m> On
      the other hand, since <me>
        e^{-\int_{x_0}^x a_1(t)\, dt} &gt;0 \quad \mbox{ for all } x \mbox{ in } I,
      </me>
      it follows that <m>W(x) &lt;0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m> if <m>W(x_0)&lt;0,</m> and <m>W(x)
      &gt;0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m> I</m> if <m>W(x_0)&gt;0.</m> Thus, either <m>W(x)</m> is
      identically zero or it does not change its sign in <m>I.</m>
    </p>

    <p> The analysis of the Wronskian together with the formula <xref ref="eq-Abel-formula" /> above
      also hold for higher order homogeneous linear equations (see Section?? Higher Order). </p>

    <theorem xml:id="wronskian-linearly-independent-theorem">
      <title>(Criterion for Linearly Indepedent Solutions)</title>

      <statement>
        <p> Two solutions <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> of <men
            xml:id="homogeneous-linear-second-order-de">
            y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0,
          </men> where <m>a_1(x)</m> and <m>
          a_0(x)</m> are continuous functions on an interval <m>I,</m> are linearly independent on <m>
          I</m> if and only if <m>W(y_1, y_2)(x)\ne 0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>


    <proof>
      <p> Let <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> be linearly independent solutions of <xref
          ref="homogeneous-linear-second-order-de" /> on <m>I</m>. Suppose, for a contradiction,
        that there is a point <m>x_0</m> in <m>I</m> such that <m>W(y_1,y_2)(x_0)= 0.</m> Let <m>c_1</m>
        and <m>c_2</m> be constants. Then the linear system <men xml:id="system">
          \begin{cases} c_1 y_1(x_0) + c_2 y_2(x_0) = 0\\ c_1 y_1'(x_0) + c_2 y_2'(x_0) = 0
        \end{cases}
        </men>
        has a solution <m>c_1, c_2,</m> not both zero because the determinant of the coefficient
        matrix is zero. Fix <m>c_1, c_2</m>, not both zero, satisfying <xref ref="system" />, and
        define the function <me>
          \phi(x) = c_1 y_1(x) + c_2 y_2(x)
        </me> on <m>I.</m> By <xref
          ref="system" /> and the superposition principle, <m>y = \phi(x)</m> is a solution on <m>I</m>
        of the initial value problem <me>
          y''+a_1(x) y' + a_0(x) y = 0, \quad y(x_0) = 0,\; y'(x_0) =0.
        </me> The
        uniqueness part of Theorem <xref ref="existence-uniqueness-theorem" /> implies <m>\phi(x) =0</m>
        on <m>I,</m> that is, <me>
          c_1 y_1(x) + c_2 y_2(x) = 0
        </me> on <m>I.</m> Thus, <m>y_1</m> and <m>
        y_2</m> are linearly dependent on <m>I</m>, contradicting our assumption. Hence <m>W(y_1,y_2)(x)\neq
        0</m> for every <m>x</m> in <m>I.</m>
      </p>

      <p> Suppose that <m>W(y_1, y_2)(x)\ne 0</m> on <m>I.</m> By <xref ref="wronskian-theorem" />, <m>
        y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are linearly independent on <m>I</m>. Note that <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m>
        need not be solutions <xref ref="homogeneous-linear-second-order-de" /> for this part of the
        theorem to hold. </p>
    </proof>
  </introduction>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-existence-of-fundamental-sets-of-solutions">
    <title>Existence of Fundamental Sets of Solutions</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-fundamental-set">
      <statement>
        <p> Consider the second order homogeneous linear differential equation <me>
            y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0,
          </me> where <m>a_1(x)</m> and <m>
          a_0(x)</m> are continuous functions on an interval <m>I.</m> Two solutions <m>y_1</m> and <m>
          y_2</m> that are linearly independent on <m>I</m> are said to form a <term>
            <em>fundamental set of solutions</em>
          </term> of the differential equation.
          Each of these solutions, <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m>, is referred to as a fundamental
          solution. </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p> An important question arises: does a fundamental set of solutions always exist? The
      following theorem ensures the existence of a fundamental set of solutions for second order
      homogeneous linear equations when <m>a_1(x)</m> and <m>a_0(x)</m> are continuous. These
      concepts extend naturally to higher order equations. </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-existence-fundamental-solution-set">
      <statement>
        <p> Consider the second order homogeneous linear differential equation <men
            xml:id="second-order-linear-homogeneous-de">
            y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0,
          </men> where <m>a_1(x)</m> and <m>
          a_0(x)</m> are continuous functions on an interval <m>I.</m> Then there exist two
          functions <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> on <m>I</m> that form a fundamental set of solutions
          for <xref ref="second-order-linear-homogeneous-de" />. </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>


    <proof>
      <p> By <xref ref="existence-uniqueness-theorem" />, there exists a unique solutions of <m>y_1</m>
        the initial value problem <me>
          y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0, \quad y(x_0) = 1,\; y'(x_0) = 0,
        </me> and
        a unique <m>y_2</m> of the initial value problem <me>
          y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0, \quad y(x_0) = 0,\; y'(x_0) = 1.
        </me> The
        two solutions <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are linearly independent on <m>I.</m> In fact, let <m>c_1,
        c_2</m> be constants such that <m>c_1y_1(x) + c_2y_2( x) = 0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I.</m>
        Since <m>x_0</m> is in <m>I,</m> we have <m>c_1y_1(x_0) + c_2y_2( x_0) = 0,</m> which
        implies <m>c_1 =0</m>. We then only have <m>c_2y_2(x) = 0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I.</m>
        Differentiating <m>c_2y_2( x) = 0</m> yields <m>c_2 y'_2(x) = 0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>
        I.</m> Since <m>y'_2(x_0) = 1,</m> we must have <m>c_2 = 0.</m> Thus, <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m>
        forms a fundamental set of solutions for <xref ref="second-order-linear-homogeneous-de" />
        on <m>I.</m>
      </p>

      <p> Let <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> be a fundamental set of solutions of <xref
          ref="second-order-linear-homogeneous-de" /> on the interval <m>I,</m> where both <m>a_0(x)</m>
        and <m>a_1(x)</m> are continuous. Denote by <m>W(x)</m> the Wronskian of <m>y_1</m> and <m>
        y_2</m>. Let <m>x_0</m> be a point in <m>I.</m> Since <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are linearly
        independent on <m>I,</m> we have <m>W(x_0)\ne 0.</m> Then the Wronskian <m>\widetilde{W}(x)</m>
        of <m>\frac{1}{ W(x_0)}y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> is <me>
          \begin{split} \widetilde{W}(x) &amp;=\frac{y_1(x) }{W(x_0)} y'_2(x) -\frac{y'_1(x)
        }{W(x_0)} y_2(x)\\ &amp; = \frac{W(x)}{W(x_0)}.
          \end{split}
        </me>
        Obviously, <m>\widetilde{W}(x_0)=1.</m> Hence we have <me>
          \widetilde{W}(x) = \widetilde{W}(x_0) e^{-\int_{x_0}^x a_1(t)\, dt} =e^{-\int_{x_0}^x
        a_1(t)\, dt}.
        </me>
        Thus, the solutions in a fundamental set can be scaled so that the Wronskian of the scaled
        solutions is <md>
          e^{-\int_{x_0}^x a_1(t)\, dt},
        </md> where <m>x_0</m> is a fixed point in <m>
        I.</m>
      </p>
    </proof>

    <example xml:id="eg-wronskian-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the Wronskian of a fundamental set of solutions of each of the following differential
          equations.
        </p>

        <p>
          <ol marker="i.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y''+\frac{2}{x}y'+\frac{10}{x^2}y = 0</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y''+\ln x\, y'+ 10 y =0</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y''-2xy'+5y = 0</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> (i) Take <m>x_0= 1</m> in <m>(0, \infty).</m> There is a fundamental set of solutions
          whose Wronskian is <me>
            e^{-\int_1^x a_1(t)\, dt} = e^{-\int_1^x \frac{2}{t}\, dt} = e^{-2 \ln x}=
            \frac{1}{x^2}.
          </me>
          <!-- linebreak -->(ii)
          Take <m>x_0= 1</m> in <m>(0, \infty).</m> There is a fundamental set of solutions whose
          Wronskian is <me>
            e^{-\int_1^x a_1(t)\, dt} =e^{-\int_1^x \ln t\, dt} = e^{x-x\ln x-1}.
          </me>
          <!-- linebreak -->(iii)
          Take <m>x_0= 0</m> in <m>(-\infty, \infty).</m> There is a fundamental set of solutions
          whose Wronskian is <me>
            e^{-\int_0^x a_1(t)\, dt} =e^{-\int_0^x (-2 t)\, dt} =e^{x^2}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      The next theorem provides a method for finding the general solutions of second order
      homogeneous linear differential equations.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-general-solution">
      <statement>
        <p> Let <m>\{y_1,y_2 \}</m> form a fundamental set of solutions of the second order
          homogeneous linear differential equation <men xml:id="eq-homogeneous-3">
            y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0,
          </men> where <m>a_1(x)</m> and <m>
          a_0(x)</m> are continuous functions on an interval <m>I.</m> Then the functions of the
          form <men xml:id="eq-homogeneous-general-solution">
            y = c_1 y_1(x) + c_2 y_2(x)
          </men> are solutions on <m>I</m> for
          any constants <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>. Moreover, every solution of <xref
            ref="eq-homogeneous-3" /> is of form <xref ref="eq-homogeneous-general-solution" /> for
          some constants <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>. </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>


    <proof>
      <p> For any <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> constants, the <xref
          ref="superposition-principle-theorem" /> implies that <men>
          y = c_1 y_1(x) + c_2 y_2(x)
        </men> is a solution of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-3" /> on <m>I.</m>
      </p>

      <p> To show that every solution of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous-3" /> is of this form <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-general-solution" />, let <m>\phi(x)</m> be a solution of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-3" /> on <m>I</m> and <m>x_0</m> be in <m>I.</m> Denote by <m>a</m>
        and <m>b</m> the constants <m>\phi(x_0)</m> and <m>\phi'(x_0)</m>, respectively. Then <m>y =
        \phi(x)</m> solves the initial value problem <men xml:id="eq-homogeneous-ivp-1">
          y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0, \quad y(x_0) = a, y'(x_0) =b.
        </men> On the
        other hand, let <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> be constants to be determined so that <m>y(x) =
        c_1y_1(x)+ c_2y_2(x)</m> satisfies <m>y(x_0) = a, y'(x_0) = b.</m> Then <me>
          \begin{cases} c_1y_1(x_0) +c_2y_2(x_0) = a,\\ c_1y'_1(x_0) +c_2y'_2(x_0) = b.\\
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        Since <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> is a linearly independent set of solutions, <xref
          ref="wronskian-theorem" /> implies <m>W(y_1, y_2)(x_0)\ne 0,</m> and therefore, by the
        Cramer’s rule, we find the unique values of <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> given by <me>
          c_1 = \frac{ \begin{vmatrix} a &amp; y_2(x_0) \\ b&amp; y_2'(x_0) \end{vmatrix}}{W(y_1,
        y_2)(x_0)} \mbox{ and } c_2 = \frac{ \begin{vmatrix} y_1(x_0)&amp;a \\ y_1'(x_0)&amp;b
        \end{vmatrix}}{W(y_1, y_2)(x_0)}.
        </me>
        With these values of <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>, the function <m>y= c_1 y_1 + c_2 y_2</m>
        solves the same initial value problem <xref ref="eq-homogeneous-ivp-1" /> as <m>\phi(x)</m>.
        By the uniqueness part of Theorem <xref ref="existence-uniqueness-theorem" />, we conclude
        that <m>\phi(x) = c_1 y_1(x) + c_2 y_2(x)</m> on <m>I.</m>
      </p>
    </proof>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-construction-fundamental-solutions">
    <title>Constructing Fundamental Sets of Solutions</title>

    <p> We now discuss methods for determining fundamental sets of solutions for second order
      homogeneous linear differential equations with constant coefficients, specifically <men
        xml:id="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1">
        ay''+by'+cy =0,
      </men> where <m>a, b, c</m> are constant coefficients and <m>a\ne
      0.</m> This equation can equivalently be written in the standard form <men
        xml:id="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-2">
        y''+\frac{b}{a}y'+\frac{c}{a}y =0.
      </men> Because the coefficient functions are
      constants and defined on <m>(-\infty, \infty),</m> the interval <m>I</m> in the existence and
      uniqueness theorem (<xref ref="existence-uniqueness-theorem" />) for <xref
        ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" /> is the entire set of real numbers <m>(-\infty,
      \infty).</m> Consequently, the solutions in any fundamental set are defined on <m>(-\infty,
      \infty).</m>
    </p>

    <p> Motivated from first order linear equations, we expect that solutions appear as exponential
      functions. So, we let <m>y = e^{\lambda x}</m> be a <em>trial</em> solution of <xref
        ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" /> for some number (possibly complex) <m>
      \lambda.</m> Differentiating <m>y = e^{\lambda x}</m> twice with respect to <m>x</m> and
      substituting <m>y, y',y''</m> into <xref ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" />
      yields <me>
        (a\lambda^2+ b\lambda +c)e^{\lambda x} = 0
      </me> for all <m>x</m> in <m>(-\infty,
      \infty).</m> In particular, when <m>x=0,</m> we obtain <men xml:id="eq-auxiliary-equation">
      a\lambda^2+ b\lambda +c =0,
      </men> which is called the <term>
        <em>auxiliary</em>
      </term> (or <term>
        <em>characteristic</em>) </term><fn> The polynomial <m>p(\lambda) = a\lambda^2+b\lambda+c</m>
      is called the <term>
          <em>characteristic polynomial</em>
        </term> for the differential equation <m>
      ay''+by'+cy=0</m>. </fn> equation for <xref ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" />.
      The roots<fn>
        <em>Solutions</em> would be a more precise term, but we use <em>
          <term>roots</term>
        </em> here to avoid confusion with solutions of differential
      equations. </fn> of <xref ref="eq-auxiliary-equation" /> are given by <men
        xml:id="eq-auxiliary-equation-solutions">
        \lambda=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a},
      </men> which are <term>
        <em>distinct real</em>
      </term>, <term>
        <em>complex</em>
      </term>, or <term>
        <em>repeated</em>
      </term> according as <m>b^2-4ac&gt;0</m>, <m>b^2-4ac&lt;0</m>, or <m>
      b^2-4ac=0</m>. We now construct a fundamental set of solutions for each case. </p>


    <paragraphs xml:id="case-i-b2-4ac0-distinct-real-roots">
      <title>Case I. <m>b^2-4ac&gt;0</m> (Distinct Real Roots)</title>

      <p> When <m>b^2-4ac&gt;0</m>, the auxiliary equation <xref ref="eq-auxiliary-equation" />
        possesses two distinct real roots <m>\lambda_1</m> and <m>\lambda_2</m> given by <xref
          ref="eq-auxiliary-equation-solutions" />. Take <men
          xml:id="eq-auxiliary-equation-solutions-real">
          \lambda_1= -\frac{b}{2a}+ \frac{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a} \quad\mbox{and}\quad
        \lambda_2=-\frac{b}{2a}- \frac{\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}.
        </men>
        Since <m>\lambda_1\ne \lambda_2,</m> it follows that <m> y_1=e^{\lambda_1x}</m> and <m>
        y_2=e^{\lambda_2x}</m> are linearly independent solutions of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" />. We confirm the linear independence of <m>
        y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> by evaluating their Wronskian: <me>
          W(y_1,y_2)(x) = \begin{vmatrix} e^{\lambda_1x}&amp;e^{\lambda_2x}\\ \lambda_1
        e^{\lambda_1x}&amp;\lambda_2e^{\lambda_2x} \end{vmatrix} =
        (\lambda_2-\lambda_1)e^{\lambda_1x} e^{\lambda_2x} \ne 0
        </me>
        on <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>. Therefore, <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> is a fundamental set of
        solutions. By <xref ref="thm-general-solution" />, the general solution of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" /> is <men
          xml:id="eq-real-distict-general-solution">
          \boxed{y = c_1e^{\lambda_1x}+c_2e^{\lambda_2x},}
        </men> where <m>c_1</m>
        and <m>c_2</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
    </paragraphs>


    <paragraphs xml:id="case-ii-b2-4ac0-complex-roots">
      <title>Case II. <m>b^2-4ac&lt;0</m> (Complex Roots)</title>

      <p> When <m>b^2-4ac&lt;0</m>, we have <m>\sqrt{b^2-4ac}= i\sqrt{4ac-b^2},</m> where <m>i =
        \sqrt{-1}</m>, the imaginary unit in the complex number system. Then the auxiliary equation <xref
          ref="eq-auxiliary-equation" /> possesses two distinct complex roots <m>\lambda_1</m> and <m>
        \lambda_2</m> given by <xref ref="eq-auxiliary-equation-solutions" />. Take <men
          xml:id="eq-auxiliary-equation-solutions-complex">
          \lambda_1= -\frac{b}{2a}+ i\frac{\sqrt{4ac-b^2}}{2a} \quad\mbox{and}\quad
        \lambda_2=-\frac{b}{2a}- i\frac{\sqrt{4ac-b^2}}{2a}.
        </men>
        Let <me>
          \alpha = -\frac{b}{2a} \quad \mbox{and}\quad \beta =\frac{\sqrt{4ac-b^2}}{2a}.
        </me>
        It is evident that <m>\beta \ne 0.</m> Then the roots <m>\lambda_1=\alpha+ i\beta</m> and <m>\lambda_2=\alpha
        - i \beta</m> of the auxiliary equation <xref ref="eq-auxiliary-equation" /> give the
        complex-valued solutions <m>z_1=e^{\lambda_1x}</m> and <m>z_2=e^{\lambda_2x}</m> of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" />. To extract real-valued solutions, we use
        first use the Euler formula <me>
          e^{i\theta} = \cos \theta + i \sin \theta, \quad \theta \mbox{ in radian,}
        </me>
        and write <me>
          \begin{split} z_1&amp;=e^{\lambda_1x} = e^{(\alpha+ i\beta)x} = e^{\alpha x} e^{i\beta x}
        =e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta x)+ ie^{\alpha x}\sin(\beta x), \mbox{and }\\
        z_2&amp;=e^{\lambda_1x} = e^{(\alpha- i\beta)x} = e^{\alpha x} e^{-i\beta x} =e^{\alpha x}
        \cos(\beta x)- ie^{\alpha x}\sin(\beta x).
          \end{split}
        </me>
        It is evident that <me>
          z_1 + z_2 =2e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta x) \quad\mbox{and}\quad z_1 - z_2 =2ie^{\alpha x}
        \sin(\beta x),
        </me>
        which imply <me>
          \begin{split} e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta x) &amp;=\frac{1}{2}\left(z_1+z_2\right)=
        \frac{1}{2}z_1 + \frac{1}{2}z_2\\ e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta
        x)&amp;=\frac{1}{2i}\left(z_1-z_2\right)=\frac{1}{2i}z_1 - \frac{1}{2i}z_2.
          \end{split}
        </me>
        Since <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> are solutions of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-2" /> (and equivalently of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" />), it follows from the superposition
        principle (<xref ref="superposition-principle-theorem" />) that <m>e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta
          x)</m> and <m>e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta x)</m> are solutions of the homogeneous equation <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" />. Denote <m>y_1=e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta x)</m>
        and <m>y_2=e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta x).</m> Then <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are linearly
        independent solutions because their Wronskian satisfies <me>
          \begin{split} W(y_1,y_2)(x) &amp;= \begin{vmatrix} e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta
          x)&amp;e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta x)\\ -\beta e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta x) +\alpha e^{\alpha x}
        \cos(\beta x) &amp;\beta e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta x) +\alpha e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta x)
        \end{vmatrix}\\ &amp;=e^{2\alpha x} \beta\\ &amp;\ne 0 \end{split}
        </me>
        for all <m>x</m> in <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>. Thus, <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> is a fundamental set
        of solutions. By <xref ref="thm-general-solution" />, the general solution of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" /> is <men
          xml:id="eq-complex-general-solution">
          \boxed{y = c_1e^{\alpha x} \cos(\beta x)+c_2e^{\alpha x} \sin(\beta x) = e^{\alpha x}
        \big(c_1\cos(\beta x)+c_2 \sin(\beta x)\big),}
        </men>
        where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
    </paragraphs>


    <paragraphs xml:id="case-iii-b2-4ac0-repeated-root">
      <title>Case III. <m>b^2-4ac=0</m> (Repeated Root)</title>

      <p> In this case, the auxiliary equation <xref ref="eq-auxiliary-equation" /> has a repeated
        real root <me>
          \lambda_1 = \lambda_2 = -\frac{b}{2a},
        </me> as given in <xref
          ref="eq-auxiliary-equation-solutions" />. Consequently, we obtain only a single solution: <me>
        y_1 = e^{\lambda_1 x} = e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x}.
        </me> Since a fundamental set
        of solutions for <xref ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" /> requires two linearly
        independent solutions, we must determine a second solution <m>y_2</m> so that <m>\{y_1,
          y_2\}</m> forms a fundamental set of solutions. </p>

      <p> We next discuss a method known as <term>
          <em>reduction of order</em>
        </term>, which allows us to find a second linearly
        independent solution of a second order homogeneous linear differential equation, even when
        the equation has variable coefficients, as in <xref ref="eq-second-order-linear-homo-de-2" />,
        given that one nontrivial solution is already known. </p>

      <p> Let <m>y_1(x)</m> be a known solution of <men xml:id="eq-second-order-linear-homo-de-2">
        y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0,
        </men> where <m>a_0(x)</m> and <m>a_1(x)</m>
        are continuous functions on an interval <m>I,</m> satisfying either <m>y_1(x)&gt;0</m> for
        all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m> or <m>y_1(x) &lt;0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m>. <xref
          ref="existence-uniqueness-theorem" /> guarantees the existence of such a nonzero solution
        on <m>I</m> for the initial condition <m>y(x_0) = y_0 \neq 0.</m> We assume <m>y_1(x) &gt; 0</m>
        on <m>I</m>; the other case can be treated similarly. </p>

      <p> Our goal is to find a second solution <m>y_2</m> such that <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> is linearly
        independent on <m>I.</m> To this end, let <m>u(x)</m> be a function on <m>I</m> such that <m>y_2
        (x) = u(x) y_1(x)</m> is a solution of <xref ref="eq-second-order-linear-homo-de-2" />. If
        we find a non-constant function <m>u,</m> then it will follow that <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> is a
        fundamental set of solutions. Then, suppressing <m>x</m> from the arguments for simplicity,
        we have <me>
          \begin{split} y'_2 &amp;= u' y_1 + u y'_1\quad \mbox{ and }\\ y''_2 &amp;= u'' y_1 +2u'
        y'_1+ u y''_1.
          \end{split}
        </me>
        Substituting these into <xref ref="eq-second-order-linear-homo-de-2" /> gives <me>
          u'' y_1 +2u' y'_1+ u y''_1 +a_1u' y_1 + a_1u y'_1 + a_0 u y_1=0.\,
        </me>
        which becomes <me>
          u'' y_1 +u'\big(2 y'_1+ a_1y_1\big) +u\big( y''_1 + a_1 y'_1+ a_0 y_1\big) =0.
        </me>
        Since <m>y_1</m> is a solution of <xref ref="eq-second-order-linear-homo-de-2" />, we have <m>y''_1
        + a_1 y'_1 +a_0 y_1 = 0,</m> and therefore we obtain <me>
          u'' y_1 +u'\Big(2 y'_1 +a_1y_1\Big) =0.
        </me> We observe that there is no <m>
        u</m> in this equation. Let <m>v = u'.</m> Then the equation becomes <me>
          v' y_1 +v\Big(2 y'_1 +a_1y_1\Big) =0,
        </me> which is of the first order.
        Since <m>y_1</m> never vanishes on <m>I</m>, we can rewrite the above equation as <men
          xml:id="eq-reduction-or-order">
          v' +\left(\frac{2 y'_1 +a_1y_1}{y_1}\right) v =0.
        </men> A solution of <xref
          ref="eq-reduction-or-order" /> is given by <me>
          v(x) = e^{-\int\left(2\frac{y'_1(x)}{y_1(x)}+a_1(x)\right)dx}=
        e^{-2\ln\lvert{y_1(x)}\rvert} \; e^{-\int a_1(x)\, dx}= \frac{e^{-\int a_1(x)\,
        dx}}{[y_1(x)]^2}.
        </me>
        Since <m>v(x) = u'(x),</m> we obtain <me>
          u(x) = \int \frac{e^{-\int a_1(x)\, dx}}{[y_1(x)]^2}\, dx
        </me> on <m>I,</m>
        and consequently, the solution <m>y_2(x)</m> is given by <men
          xml:id="eq-reduction-of-order-formula">
          \boxed{y_2(x) = y_1(x) \int \frac{e^{-\int a_1(x)\, dx}}{[y_1(x)]^2}\, dx.}
        </men>
        on <m>I.</m><fn> This formula is due the French mathematician Joseph Liouville </fn> Thus, <m>\{y_1,
        y_2\}</m> is a fundamental set of solutions for <xref ref="eq-second-order-linear-homo-de-2" />
        .<!-- linebreak --> We now return to finding a second linearly independent solution <m>y_2</m> for <term>Case
        III</term>. Since <me>
          y_1 = e^{\lambda_1 x} = e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x}
        </me> and <m>a_1(x) =
        \frac{b}{a}</m> is a constant, the reduction of the order formula <xref
          ref="eq-reduction-of-order-formula" /> gives <me>
          y_2(x) = e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x} \int \frac{e^{-\int (b/a)\, dx}}{e^{-\frac{b}{a}x}}\, dx =
        e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x} \int 1\, dx = x e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x}
        </me>
        on <m>I</m>. Since we only need a second solution <m>y_2</m>, the constants of integration
        are set to zero for convenience. Thus, <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> forms a fundamental set of
        solutions. By <xref ref="thm-general-solution" />, the general solution of <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous-constant-coefficients-1" /> is <men
          xml:id="eq-repeated-roots-general-solution">
          \boxed{ y = c_1 e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x} + c_2 x e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x} = (c_1 + c_2 x)
        e^{-\frac{b}{2a}x},}
        </men>
        where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>
      An alternative method for finding a second linearly independent solution when the
      characteristic polynomial has a repeated root is outlined in Exercises.
    </p>

    <remark>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p> The method discussed above for finding <m>u(x)</m> is known as the <term>reduction
                of order</term> because the resulting differential equation <xref
                ref="eq-reduction-or-order" /> for <m>v(x)</m> is of first order; one order less
              than that of the original equation <xref ref="eq-second-order-linear-homo-de-2" />. </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="rem-Abel-formula">
            <p> If the known solution <m>y_1</m> vanishes at some points in the interval <m>I</m>,
              we can first apply the reduction of the order on a subinterval <m>J</m> of <m>I</m>
              where <m>y_1</m> does not change sign, and then extend the solution to all of <m>I</m>
              using a theorem on continuation of solutions (which is beyond the scope of this book).
              In practice, we may formally compute <m>y_2(x)</m> using <xref
                ref="eq-reduction-of-order-formula" /> and then verify that <m>y_2</m> is actually
              well-defined on the entire interval <m>I</m>. For this, see <xref
                ref="eg-order-reduction" />. </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="eg-general-solution-1">
      <statement>
        <p> Find the general solution of <me>
            y''-16y = 0.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Assume a solution of the form <m>y = e^{\lambda x}</m>. Then <m>y' = \lambda e^{\lambda
          x}</m> and <m>y'' = \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x}</m>. Substituting into the differential
          equation gives <me>
            \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x} - 16 e^{\lambda x} = 0,
          </me> which gives <me>
          (\lambda^2 - 16) e^{\lambda x} = 0.
          </me> Since <m>e^{\lambda x}
            \neq 0</m>, the auxiliary equation that we obtain is <me>
            \lambda^2 - 16 = 0,
          </me> whose distinct real roots are <me>
          \lambda_1 = 4\quad\mbox{and}\quad \lambda_2 =-4.
          </me> By <xref
            ref="eq-real-distict-general-solution" />, the general solution is <me>
            y(x) = c_1 e^{4x} + c_2 e^{-4x},
          </me> where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>
          are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-general-solution-2">
      <statement>
        <p> Find the general solution of <me>
            y''-y'-6y = 0.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Assume a solution of the form <m>y = e^{\lambda x}</m>. Then <m>y' = \lambda e^{\lambda
          x}</m> and <m>y'' = \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x}</m>. Substituting into the differential
          equation gives <me>
            \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x} - 16 e^{\lambda x} = 0,
          </me> which gives <me>
          (\lambda^2 - 16) e^{\lambda x} = 0.
          </me> Since <m>e^{\lambda x}
            \neq 0</m>, the auxiliary equation that we obtain is <me>
            \lambda^2 - 16 = 0,
          </me> whose distinct real roots are <me>
          \lambda_1 = 4\quad\mbox{and}\quad \lambda_2 =-4.
          </me> By <xref
            ref="eq-real-distict-general-solution" />, the general solution is <me>
            y(x) = c_1 e^{4x} + c_2 e^{-4x},
          </me> where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>
          are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-general-solution-3">
      <statement>
        <p> Find the general solution of <me>
            3y''+2y'+y = 0.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Assume a solution of the form <m>y = e^{\lambda x}</m>. Then <m>y' = \lambda e^{\lambda
          x}</m> and <m>y'' = \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x}</m>. Substituting into the differential
          equation gives <me>
            (3\lambda^2 + 2\lambda + 1)e^{\lambda x} = 0.
          </me> Then the
          auxiliary equation is <me>
            3\lambda^2 + 2\lambda + 1=0,
          </me> whose complex roots are <me>
          \lambda = \frac{-2 \pm \sqrt{-8}}{6} = \frac{-1 \pm \sqrt{2} i}{3} = -\frac{1}{3} \pm i
          \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3}.
          </me>
          Substituting <m>\alpha = -\frac{1}{3}</m> and <m>\beta = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3}</m> in <xref
            ref="eq-complex-general-solution" />, the general solution is <me>
            y = e^{-x/3} \left( c_1 \cos \left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} x\right) + c_2 \sin
          \left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} x\right) \right),
          </me>
          where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-general-solution-4">
      <statement>
        <p> Find the general solution of <me>
            y''+8y'+16y = 0.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Assume a solution of the form <m>y = e^{\lambda x}</m>. Then <m>y' = \lambda e^{\lambda
          x}</m> and <m>y'' = \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x}</m>. Substituting into the differential
          equation gives <me>
            \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x} + 8\lambda e^{\lambda x} + 16 e^{\lambda x} = 0,
          </me>
          which gives <me>
            (\lambda^2 + 8\lambda + 16) e^{\lambda x} = 0.
          </me> Since <m>e^{\lambda
          x} \neq 0</m>, the auxiliary equation that we obtain is <me>
            \lambda^2 + 8\lambda + 16 = 0,
          </me> whose repeated real root is <me>
          \lambda = -4.
          </me> By <xref
            ref="eq-repeated-roots-general-solution" />, the general solution is <me>
            y(x) = (c_1 + c_2 x) e^{-4x},
          </me> where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>
          are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-order-reduction">
      <statement>
        <p> Given that <m>y_1 = \sin x</m> solves <m>y'' + y = 0</m> on <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>,
          find a second linearly independent solution using the formula <xref
            ref="eq-reduction-of-order-formula" /> for the reduction of the order. </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> For <m>y'' + y = 0</m>, we have <m>a_1 =0.</m> Also, the given solution <m>y_1 = \sin x</m>
          vanishes at the points <m>x = n\pi,</m> <m>n= 0, \pm 1, \pm 2, \dots.</m> Therefore, we
          restrict <m>y_1</m> to an interval <m>J</m> not containing these points. For example, take <m>J
          = (0, \pi).</m> Applying the formula <xref ref="eq-reduction-of-order-formula" />, a
          second solution <m>y_2</m> is given by <me>
            \begin{split}y_2(x) &amp;= \sin x \int \frac{1}{\sin^2x}\, dx\\ &amp; = \sin x \int
          \csc^2 x\, dx= -\sin x \cot x\\ &amp; = -\cos x\end{split}
          </me>
          on <m>J.</m> By scaling, we redefine <m>y_2 = \cos x</m> on <m>J=(0, \pi).</m> Since <m>y_2=
          \cos x</m> can be extended by the same formula to all of <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m> and <me>
          W(\cos x, \sin x) = 1\ne 0
          </me> for all <m>x</m> in <m>(-\infty,
          \infty),</m> it follows <xref ref="wronskian-theorem" /> that <m>y_1= \sin x</m> and <m>y_2
          = \cos x</m> are linearly independent on <m>(-\infty, \infty).</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p> Techniques for finding fundamental sets of solutions for homogeneous linear equations with
      variable coefficients are discussed in <xref ref="sec-3-6" />. In this section, we will only
      discuss the <term>Cauchy–Euler</term> equations of the form <men
        xml:id="eq-Cauchy-Euler">
        x^2y''+b xy' +cy =0,\quad x&gt;0,
      </men> where <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are real
      constants. The method uses <m>y = x^\lambda</m> as a trial solution, with <m>\lambda</m> to be
      determined from the auxiliary equation <me>
        \lambda^2 +(b-1)\lambda +c=0,
      </me> whose roots are real and distinct, complex,
      or repeated according as <me>
        (b-1)^2-4c&gt;0,\;\; (b-1)^2-4c&lt;0,\;\; \mbox{ or } (b-1)^2-4c=0.
      </me> We
      next discuss three examples, one for each case. </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-Cauchy-Euler">
      <statement>
        <p> Find the general solution of the Cauchy-Euler equation <md>
            x^2 y''+4xy'+y = 0,\quad x&gt;0.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Take <m>y = x^\lambda</m> as a trial solution, where <m>\lambda</m> is a number to be
          determined. Differentiating <m>y = x^\lambda</m> twice with respect to <m>x</m> and
          substituting <m>y, y', y''</m> into the differential equation, we obtain <me>
            (\lambda^2+ 3\lambda +1)x^\lambda =0
          </me> for all <m>x</m> in an
          interval <m>I,</m> so the auxiliary equation is <me>
            \lambda^2+ 3\lambda +1=0
          </me> with roots <me>
            \lambda = \frac{-3\pm \sqrt{5}}{2}.
          </me> Let <me>
          \lambda_1=\frac{-3+ \sqrt{5}}{2}\quad\mbox{and}\quad\lambda_2=\frac{-3- \sqrt{5}}{2}.
          </me>
          Obviously, <m>\lambda_1&lt;0</m> and <m>\lambda_2&lt;0.</m> From the two options <m>
          (-\infty,0)</m> and <m>(0, \infty),</m> let us take <m>I = (0, \infty).</m> Then <m>y_1 =
          x^{\lambda_1}</m> and <m>\lambda_2 = x^{\lambda_2}</m> are solutions on <m>I,</m> and
          their Wronskian <me>
            \begin{split} W(y_1, y_2)(x) &amp;= \begin{vmatrix} x^{\lambda_1}&amp;x^{\lambda_2}\\
          \lambda_1x^{\lambda_1-1}&amp;\lambda_2x^{\lambda_2-1} \end{vmatrix} \\ &amp;=
          (\lambda_2-\lambda_1) x^{(\lambda_1+\lambda_2-2)}\\ &amp;=(\lambda_2-\lambda_1) x^{-5}\\
          &amp; \ne 0 \end{split}
          </me>
          for all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m> since <m>\lambda_1+\lambda_2 = -3</m>. Thus <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m>
          is a fundamental set of solutions, and therefore the general solution of the Cauchy-Euler
          equation is <me>
            y = c_1x^{\lambda_1}+c_2x^{\lambda_2} = c_1x^{\frac{-3+ \sqrt{5}}{2}}+c_2x^{\frac{-3-
          \sqrt{5}}{2}}
          </me>
          on <m>I,</m> where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-Cauchy-Euler-complex">
      <statement>
        <p> Solve the Cauchy–Euler equation <md>
            x^2 y'' - y' + 5y = 0, \quad x&gt;0.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Let <m>y = x^\lambda</m> be a trial solution. Then <me>
            y' = \lambda x^{\lambda-1}, \qquad y'' = \lambda(\lambda-1)x^{\lambda-2}.
          </me>
          Substituting into the differential equation gives <me>
            (\lambda^2 - 2\lambda + 5)x^\lambda = 0.
          </me> Then the auxiliary
          equation is <me>
            \lambda^2 - 2\lambda + 5=0
          </me> whose solutions are </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \lambda = \frac{2 \pm \sqrt{-16}}{2} = 1 \pm 2i.
          </me> For complex
          numbers <m>\lambda = 1 \pm 2i</m>, we have <me>
            x^{1 \pm 2i}= x\, x^{\pm 2i}= x e^{\pm 2i\ln x} = x\big(\cos(2 \ln x) \pm i \sin(2\ln
          x)\big).
          </me>
          Let <m>y_1 = x\cos(2 \ln x)</m> and <m>y_2 = x\sin(2 \ln x).</m> It is routine to verify
          that <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are linearly independent solutions on <m>(0, \infty).</m>
          Then the general solution of the Cauchy–Euler equation is <me>
            y(x) = x \big(c_1 \cos(2 \ln x) + c_2 \sin(2 \ln x)\big), \quad x&gt;0,
          </me>
          where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-Cauchy-Euler-repeated-roots">
      <statement>
        <p> Solve the Cauchy–Euler equation <md>
            x^2 y'' - y' + y = 0, \quad x&gt;0.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Let <m>y = x^\lambda</m> be a trial solution. Then <me>
            y' = \lambda x^{\lambda-1}, \qquad y'' = \lambda(\lambda-1)x^{\lambda-2}.
          </me>
          Substituting into the differential equation yields <me>
            (\lambda^2 - 2\lambda + 1)x^\lambda = 0.
          </me> Then the auxiliary
          equation is <me>
            \lambda^2 - 2\lambda + 1=0,\quad \mbox{i.e.},\; (\lambda-1)^2 = 0.
          </me>
          Its solutions are <me>
            \lambda = 1, 1 \; (\text{repeated})
          </me> We thus have one solution
          as <m>y_1= x.</m> By the reduction of the order formula <xref
            ref="eq-reduction-of-order-formula" />, a second linearly independent solution <m>y_2</m>
          is given by <me>
            \begin{split} y_2&amp;= y_1 \int \frac{e^{-\int a_1(x)\, dx}}{y_1^2}\, dx\quad
            \mbox{with } a_1(x) = -\frac{1}{x}\\ &amp;= x \int \frac{e^{-\int
          \left(-\frac{1}{x}\right)\, dx}}{x^2}\, dx\\ &amp;=x \int \frac{1}{x}\, dx\\ &amp;= x \ln
          x.
            \end{split}
          </me>
          Hence the general solution of the Cauchy-Euler equation is <me>
            y= c_1 x+c_2 x\ln x,\quad x&gt;0,
          </me> where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>
          are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-second-order">
    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-1">
      <p> Verify that the indicated solution set for each differential equation below is linearly
        independent on the specified interval <m>I</m> by computing Wronskian of the solutions (see <xref
          ref="wronskian-linearly-independent-theorem" />). <ol marker="i.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''=0</m>, <m>\{7,\, x\}, \qquad I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+y=0</m>, <m>\{\sin x,\, \cos x\}, \qquad I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+y=0</m>, <m>\{\sin x,\, \sin x+\cos x\}, \qquad I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-4y=0</m>, <m>\{e^{2x},\, e^{-2x}\}, \qquad I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-4y=0</m>, <m>\{e^{2x},\, e^{-2x}\}, \qquad I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-4y'+4y=0</m>, <m>\{e^{2x},\, xe^{2x}\}, \qquad I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-4y'+4y=0</m>, <m>\{e^{2x},\, (x+1)e^{2x}\}, \qquad I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-4y'+13y=0</m>, <m>\{e^{2x}\cos(3x),\, e^{2x}\sin(3x)\}, \qquad
        I=(-\infty,\infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-\frac{2}{x}y'=0</m>, <m>\{1, x^3\}, \qquad I = (0, \infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2 y''+xy'+y = 0,</m>
              <m>\{\cos(\ln x),\, \sin(\ln x)\}, \quad I = (0, \infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2 y''+4xy'+y = 0,</m>
              <m>\{x^{\frac{-3+ \sqrt{5}}{2}}, x^{\frac{-3- \sqrt{5}}{2}}\}, \qquad I = (0, \infty)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-2">
      <p> Find the general solution of each differential equation below (see <xref
          ref="thm-general-solution" />). <ol marker="i." cols="2">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-5y'+6y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+11y'+30y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2y''+5y'+3y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-7y'-30y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+4y'=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+4y'+13y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-5y'+y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2y''+5y'+y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-3">
      <p> Find the general solution of each of the following Cauchy-Euler differential equations
        (see <xref ref="eg-Cauchy-Euler" />). <ol marker="i." cols="2">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2y''+xy'-y = 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x y''-2y'=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2 y''-x y'-3y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2 y''-2y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2 y''+x y'+y=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2y''+3xy'+5y = 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-4">
      <p> Find the solution of each of the following initial value problems: <ol marker="i.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-16y =0,\; y(0)= 0, \; y'(1) = 1</m>
            </p>
            <p> (Hint: See <xref ref="eg-general-solution-1" /> for the general solution.) </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-y'-6y = 0, \;y(0)= -1, \; y'(0) = 1</m>
            </p>
            <p> (Hint: See <xref ref="eg-general-solution-2" /> for the general solution.) </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>3y''+2y'+y=0,\; y(0)=1,\; y'(0)=0</m>
            </p>
            <p> (Hint: See <xref ref="eg-general-solution-3" /> for the general solution.) </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+8y'+16y = 0,\; y(1)=1,\; y'(1)=-1</m>
            </p>
            <p> (Hint: See <xref ref="eg-general-solution-4" /> for the general solution.) </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-5">
      <p> Solve the following initial value problems by using the general solutions of the related
        equations obtained in <xref ref="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-2" /> and <xref
          ref="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-3" />. <ol marker="i.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-5y'+6y=0, \quad y(0) = 0, \quad y'(0)=1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+11y'+30y=0, \quad y(0) = 0, \quad y'(0)=1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2y''+5y'+3y=0, \quad y(0) = 1, \quad y'(0)=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-7y'-30y=0, \quad y(0) = 1, \quad y'(0)=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+4y'=0, \quad y(0) = 1, \quad y'(0)=1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''+4y'+13y=0, \quad y(0) = 1, \quad y'(0)=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>y''-5y'+y=0, \quad y(0) = 0, \quad y'(0)=1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2y''+5y'+y=0, \quad y(0) = 0, \quad y'(0)=1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2y''+xy'-y = 0, \quad y(1) = 1, \quad y'(1)=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2 y''+x y'+y=0, \quad y(1) = 1, \quad y'(1)=1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2 y''-x y'-3y=0, \quad y(1) = 1, \quad y'(1)=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2y''+3xy'+5y = 0,\quad y(1) = 1, \quad y'(1)=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-6">
      <p> Suppose that the characteristic polynomial <me>p(\lambda) = a\lambda^2 + b\lambda + c</me>
        of the differential equation <me>ay'' + by' + cy = 0, \quad a \ne 0,</me> where <m>a, b, c</m>
        are constants, has a repeated root <m>\lambda_0.</m> Then <m>y_1 = e^{\lambda_0 x}</m> is a
        solution of the differential equation. To find a second linearly independent solution,
        proceed as follows. <ol marker="a.">
          <li xml:id="part-a">
            <p> Let <m>y = e^{\lambda x}</m> with parameter <m>\lambda</m>. Show that <me>a\frac{\partial^2}{\partial
        x^2} (e^{\lambda x}) + b\frac{\partial}{\partial x} (e^{\lambda x}) + c (e^{\lambda x}) =
        p(\lambda) e^{\lambda x}.</me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p> Differentiate both sides of the equation in <xref ref="part-a" /> with respect to <m>
        \lambda</m> to obtain <me>a\frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2} (x e^{\lambda x}) +
        b\frac{\partial}{\partial x} (x e^{\lambda x}) + c (x e^{\lambda x}) = \big(p'(\lambda) +
                x\, p(\lambda)\big) e^{\lambda x}.</me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p> Using <m>p(\lambda_0) = p'(\lambda_0) = 0</m>, conclude that <m>y_2 = x e^{\lambda_0
        x}</m> is also a solution. </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p> Show that <m>y_1 =e^{\lambda_0 x}</m> and <m>y_2=x e^{\lambda_0 x}</m> are linearly
        independent on <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>. </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>


    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-second-order-homogeneous-7">
      <p> Let <m>y_1(x)</m> be a known solution of <men xml:id="eq-second-order-linear_homo-de-3">
        y'' + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0,
        </men> where <m>a_0(x)</m> and <m>a_1(x)</m>
        are continuous functions on an interval <m>I,</m> satisfying <m>y_1(x)&gt;0</m> for all <m>x</m>
        in <m>I</m>. Use the Wronskian to derive Liouville’s formula <xref
          ref="eq-reduction-of-order-formula" /> as follows: <ol marker="a.">
          <li xml:id="wronskian-method">
            <p> Suppose that <m>y_2</m> is a solution of <xref
                ref="eq-second-order-linear_homo-de-3" /> such that <m>\{y_1, y_2\}</m> is linearly
        independent on <m>I.</m> Show that <me>\left(\frac{y_2}{y_1}\right)' = \frac{W(x)}{y_1^2}
        \quad \mbox{on } I,</me> where <m>W(x)</m> is the Wronskian of <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m>
        given by <m>W(x) =y_1(x)y_2'(x) - y_1'(x)y_2(x).</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="Abel-2">
            <p> Using <xref ref="wronskian-method" />, show that <me>y_2 = y_1(x)
        \int\frac{W(x)}{[y_1(x)]^2}\, dx.</me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p> Obtain Liouville’s formula <me>y_2 = y_1(x) \int\frac{e^{-\int
        a_1(x)\,dx}}{[y_1(x)]^2}\, dx</me> from part <xref ref="Abel-2" />. </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        The same steps also apply when the known solution <m>y_1</m> satisfies <m>y_1(x) &lt;0</m>
        for all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m>. For the general case, see (ii) of Remark <xref
          ref="rem-Abel-formula" />. </p>
    </exercise>

  </exercises>
</section>